Table I, page 479.
Particles emerging from the magnet were
counted in a scintillation counter using an RCA 5819
photomultiplier and a thallium activated KI crystal,
and later a CsI crystal.
The alpha particles emitted from the target at an
angle of 90 degrees to the incident beam were
analysed in a magnetic spectrometer and counted with
a scintillation detector.
The 180 is target was prepared by bombardment of a
tantalum sheet with mass 18 oxygen ions in the
magnetic separator at A.E.R.E., Harwell. The exact
thickness of the target is not known, but it appeared
from the resolution obtained in the excitation
measurements to be less than 20 keV. The oxygen in
the targets was estimated to contain 25 percent 180.
Fig. 2, page 480.
Resonant energies are accurate to 10 keV;
small differences may be  good to 2 or 3 keV.
Absolute cross section errors are estimated
to be 25 percent.
Width error of 2 keV is applicable.
Table 3, page 485.
Particles emerging from the magnet were
counted in a scintillation counter using an RCA 5819
photomultiplier and a thallium activated KI crystal,
and later a CsI crystal.
The alpha particles emitted from the target at an
angle of 90 degrees to the incident beam were
analysed in a magnetic spectrometer and counted with
a scintillation detector.
The other targets were prepared by the evaporation of
Zn3P2, the evaporation being carried
out simultaneously on backings of tantalum and
polished graphite. The measured thickness of the
target was 0.6 keV.
Fig. 5, page 484.
Particles emerging from the magnet were

The alpha particles emitted from the target at an

The other targets were prepared by the evaporation of
KCl and SnCl2, the evaporation being carried
out simultaneously on backings of tantalum and
polished graphite. The measured thickness of the
target was 10.0 keV for 2 MeV protons.
